Analysis and forecast of Harbor Beach levels

Manuel Hernandez Zemljic

Introduction

The context of this course work is the analysis of the data-set of the lake levels asked by an environmental agency, and the purpose of this analysis is to provide a forecast for the next 24 months. The data was imported from the text file provided and transformed into a time-series structure. The native R functions acf and pacf provided the autocorrelation functions and partial autocorrelation function used to detect the stationarity or nonstationarity of the data and to obtain an initial set of models to fit.

Importing the data: The data is read from a text file with spaces separator, then as it comes on rows it is needed to transpose and transform in a time series data structure.

w=read.csv("HarborBeach.txt", colClasses = "numeric", sep = " ", header = FALSE)
w=t(w)
w = unlist(w[!is.na(w)], use.names = FALSE)
harbor = ts(w, frequency = 12, start=c(1900,1), end=c(2021,1))
par(mfrow=c(3,1))
ts.plot(harbor)
acf(harbor,lag.max = 100)
pacf(harbor, lag.max = 100)

Fig. 1: Harbortime series, acf and pacf.

In figure 1 is appreciated that the acf is decaying very slowly, this pattern of the acf is a sign of nonstationary data. And also on the first graph of the figure I see a sort of trends repeated cyclically. The seasonal component is possible to visualize on the next picture of the average level per month when in June, July and August are the months with the highest lake levels of the year on average, and conversely, January, February, and March are the lowest.

x = rowMeans(ts_reshape(harbor)[,1:122])
  plot(x, xlab = "Month", ylab = "Lake level",
       main = "Harbor Beach\naverage level per month",
       ylim=c(min(x), max(x)), type="b")

Fig. 2 Harbor Beach average level per month

##Differenced data at lag 12:

harbor.diff12=diff(harbor,12)
par(mfrow=c(3,1))
plot(harbor.diff12)
acf(harbor.diff12, lag.max=30)
pacf(harbor.diff12, lag.max=30)

Fig. 3: Time series differenciated at lag 12, acf and pacf

Looking at the data differenced at lag 12 on this figure, the early lags of the acf make me think there is an AR component in the regular part of the model. An MA component in the seasonal part of the model is suggested by the spike in lag 12. The big spike at lag 1 in the pacf suggests the AR influence. The big spike at lag 12 followed by a small one mean an AR component in the seasonal part of the model as well. As I present on figure 4 I tried here the models ARIMA(1,0,2)x(0,0,1), ARIMA(1,0,2)x(2,0,1), and ARIMA(1,0,2)x(2,0,2). These models have good behavior.

fit1 = arima(harbor.diff12, order = c(1,0,2), seasonal = c(0,0,1))
fit2 = arima(harbor.diff12, order = c(1,0,2), seasonal = c(2,0,1))
fit3 = arima(harbor.diff12, order = c(1,0,2), seasonal = c(2,0,2))
tsdiag(fit1)

Fig. 4:Fitted model from differenced data at lag 12 

tsdiag(fit2)

Fig. 4:Fitted model from differenced data at lag 12 

tsdiag(fit3)

Fig. 4:Fitted model from differenced data at lag 12

Now I fitted the models with the original data and adjusting de seasonal difference to 1 (D=1) obtaining the models ARIMA(1,0,2)x(0,1,1), ARIMA(1,0,2)x(2,1,1), and ARIMA(1,0,2)x(2,1,2).

In the next figure, I report that for the three models the standardized residuals look like white noize, the acf also behaves like white noise as we have a spike at lag zero which is always present. On the other hand, the p values are higher than 0.05. Even though the p values at lag 2 are quite close to the blue dotted line, it is, like all the other values, above it, hence these models are a good fit.

fit.102.011 = arima(harbor, order = c(1,0,2), seasonal = c(0,1,1))
fit.102.211 = arima(harbor, order = c(1,0,2), seasonal = c(2,1,1))
fit.102.212 = arima(harbor, order = c(1,0,2), seasonal = c(2,1,2))

##Second approach using first and twelve differences

In this part I test models with first and twelve difference, with that aim I differentiate the data in the variable harbor.diff.diff12 and I proceed to plot the series and its respective acf and pacf. The justification for this approach is that although the data differentiated at lag twelve looks stationary there are short-term trends that I want to filter.

harbor.diff.diff12=diff(diff(harbor),12)
par(mfrow=c(3,1))
plot(harbor.diff.diff12)
acf(harbor.diff.diff12)
pacf(harbor.diff.diff12)

Fig. 6

Looking at lag one in the ACF, it has a MA component in the nonseasonal part, but one big spike followed by a small one after lag 12 means it can have also an MA1 or MA2 in the seasonal part of the model. The spike in the pacf at lag 12 is a sign of a cyclical AR component. In the next pictures, I show that the parameter d=1 is worth exploring.

fit1 = arima(harbor.diff.diff12, order = c(1,0,1), seasonal = c(1,0,1))
fit2 = arima(harbor.diff.diff12, order = c(1,0,2), seasonal = c(0,0,1))
fit3 = arima(harbor.diff.diff12, order = c(1,0,1), seasonal = c(0,0,1))
fit4 = arima(harbor.diff.diff12, order = c(1,0,1), seasonal = c(0,0,2))
fit5 = arima(harbor.diff.diff12, order = c(1,0,1), seasonal = c(1,0,2))

And finally, I show in the next output the relation \(\frac{coefficient}{s.e.}\), and because R does not include this in the report I made my own function for that purpose. Although the model ARIMA(1,0,2)x(0,1,1)_12 doesnt have a really good value in this figure, I closed it because I expect this model will have better forecast capacity and less over-fitting based on it has the lowest aic. The ARIMA(1,0,2)(0,1,1)_12 model has AR parameter \(\phi_1=0.9843\) MA parameters \(\theta_1=0.7639\) and \(\theta_2=0.0297\), and SMA parameter \(\Theta_1=0.9772\). So the models is \[(1 - \phi_1 B)(1-B^{12})X_t = (1 - \theta_1 B - \theta_2 B^2)(1 - \Theta_1 B^{12}) Z_t\] \[(1 - 0.9843 B)(1-B^{12})X_t = (1 - 0.7639 B - 0.0297 B^2)(1 - 0.9772 B^{12}) Z_t\]

modelSummary = function(models){
  for (i in 1:length(models)){
    x=paste("ARIMA (",paste(models[[i]]$call$order[2:4], collapse = ","),")",
          "(",paste(models[[i]]$call$seasonal[2:4], collapse = ","),")", collapse = "")
    w=as.data.frame(models[[i]]$coef/sqrt(diag(models[[i]]$var.coef)))
    w=t(w)
    rownames(w)=NULL
    #print(data.frame(model=x, aic=model$aic, w))
    print(x)
    print(models[[i]]$aic)
    print(w)
  }
}
modelSummary(models)

Conclusions

The model ARIMA(1,0,2)(0,1,1)_12 has been selected as the best fit for the forecast of the future 24 months levels of the lake. The auto-correlation and partial auto-correlation values were plotted for different lags. The study of these plots revealed that the data had signs of being nonstationary and that is why it was necessary to differentiate it at lag 12, converting the data into stationary. These plots were used to obtain a set of models that passed the Ljung-Box statistic, and after that, the model with the lowest Akaike Information Criterion was chosen. A table with the foretasted points and confidence intervals at 80 and 95 percent were presented.
